review.review_inline:
mm: zswap: Consistently use IS_ERR_OR_NULL() to check acomp_ctx resources.

> diff --git a/mm/zswap.c b/mm/zswap.c
> index 26de0468e33b..6c6c14433556 100644
> --- a/mm/zswap.c
> +++ b/mm/zswap.c
> @@ -786,7 +786,7 @@ static int zswap_cpu_comp_prepare(unsigned int cpu, struct hlist_node *node)
>  		return ret;
>  
>  	acomp_ctx->acomp = crypto_alloc_acomp_node(pool->tfm_name, 0, 0, cpu_to_node(cpu));
> -	if (IS_ERR(acomp_ctx->acomp)) {
> +	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->acomp)) {
>  		pr_err("could not alloc crypto acomp %s : %pe\n",
>  				pool->tfm_name, acomp_ctx->acomp);
>  		ret = PTR_ERR(acomp_ctx->acomp);
>  		goto fail;
>  	}

crypto_alloc_acomp_node() bottoms out in crypto_alloc_tfm_node(), which
always returns either a valid pointer or ERR_PTR(err) -- it never returns
NULL. So the IS_ERR_OR_NULL() change is harmless in practice, but there
is a latent correctness issue: if acomp_ctx->acomp ever were NULL,
PTR_ERR(NULL) == 0, so ret would be silently overwritten with 0 and the
function would return 0 (success) from the fail label. The original IS_ERR()
check was precise and correct here. Consistency with acomp_ctx_dealloc() is
a fine goal, but in acomp_ctx_dealloc() the IS_ERR_OR_NULL() guard is only
used to skip a free -- there is no PTR_ERR() call in that path, so the
semantics are different.

Could the IS_ERR_OR_NULL() be kept for the guard alone and PTR_ERR() be
protected with an explicit null check, e.g.:

    if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->acomp)) {
        ret = acomp_ctx->acomp ? PTR_ERR(acomp_ctx->acomp) : -ENOMEM;
        goto fail;
    }

Or alternatively, keep IS_ERR() here since the API is documented to never
return NULL?

> @@ -794,7 +794,7 @@ static int zswap_cpu_comp_prepare(unsigned int cpu, struct hlist_node *node)
>  	}
>  
>  	acomp_ctx->req = acomp_request_alloc(acomp_ctx->acomp);
> -	if (!acomp_ctx->req) {
> +	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(acomp_ctx->req)) {

acomp_request_alloc() is documented to return NULL on failure (it calls
kzalloc internally). It never returns an ERR_PTR value, so the IS_ERR
half of IS_ERR_OR_NULL() is dead code here. This check has no PTR_ERR()
call after it so ret stays -ENOMEM, which is correct. But adding an IS_ERR()
guard for a function that only returns NULL on failure may mislead future
readers into thinking ERR_PTR returns are expected. Is !acomp_ctx->req not
more accurate?

Usama Arif <usama.arif@linux.dev>

arm64/mm: contpte-sized exec folios for 16K and 64K pages

The overall direction is good and the motivation is well-explained.
Two issues worth addressing before merging:

> diff --git a/mm/filemap.c b/mm/filemap.c

[ ... ]

> +	if (vm_flags & VM_EXEC) {
> +		/*
> +		 * [...]
> +		 * This is targeted readahead (one folio at the fault location),
> +		 * not speculative prefetch, so bypass the mmap_miss heuristic
> +		 * which would otherwise disable it after MMAP_LOTSAMISS faults.
> +		 */
> +		struct vm_area_struct *vma = vmf->vma;
> +		unsigned long start = vma->vm_pgoff;
> +		unsigned long end = start + vma_pages(vma);
> +		unsigned long ra_end;
> +
> +		ra->order = exec_folio_order();
> +		ra->start = round_down(vmf->pgoff, 1UL << ra->order);
> +		ra->start = max(ra->start, start);
> +		ra_end = round_up(ra->start + ra->ra_pages, 1UL << ra->order);
> +		ra_end = min(ra_end, end);
> +		ra->size = ra_end - ra->start;
> +		ra->async_size = 0;
> +		goto do_readahead;
> +	}

This new block is placed before the force_thp_readahead block that
follows below:

  if (force_thp_readahead) {
      ra->order = HPAGE_PMD_ORDER;
      ...
      page_cache_ra_order(&ractl, ra);
      return fpin;
  }

In the pre-patch code the force_thp_readahead path ran first, so a
VM_EXEC|VM_HUGEPAGE VMA (force_thp_readahead = true) got
HPAGE_PMD_ORDER folios.  After this patch the new VM_EXEC block fires
first and takes the goto, so force_thp_readahead is never reached for
any exec VMA.

Concretely: with THP=always for file-backed mappings, or with an
explicit madvise(MADV_HUGEPAGE) on an exec segment, a fault now uses
exec_folio_order() (e.g. order 4 / 64 KB on 4K pages) instead of
HPAGE_PMD_ORDER (order 9 / 2 MB).  That silently disables PMD-sized
THP for those VMAs.

Could the VM_EXEC block be conditioned on !force_thp_readahead, or
alternatively moved to come after the force_thp_readahead block so
the original priority is preserved?

> diff --git a/fs/binfmt_elf.c b/fs/binfmt_elf.c

[ ... ]

> +			if (exec_folio_order())
> +				alignment = max(alignment,
> +					(unsigned long)PAGE_SIZE << exec_folio_order());
> +
>  			/**
>  			 * DOC: PIE handling

This alignment bump is applied before the if (interpreter) / else
branch.  The else branch (ET_DYN without PT_INTERP -- static PIE
binaries and the ELF interpreter itself when executed directly)
contains:

  if (alignment > ELF_MIN_ALIGN) {
      load_bias = elf_load(bprm->file, 0, ...);
      ...
      vm_munmap(load_bias, total_size);
      load_bias &= ~(alignment - 1);
      elf_flags |= MAP_FIXED_NOREPLACE;
  } else
      load_bias = 0;

On arm64 with 64K base pages ELF_MIN_ALIGN == PAGE_SIZE == 64K, and
exec_folio_order() returns 5, so the bumped alignment is 2M which is
> ELF_MIN_ALIGN.  For any ET_DYN-without-PT_INTERP binary whose
native maximum_alignment() was <= ELF_MIN_ALIGN (the common case for
ld.so and musl-based static PIE), the code previously set
load_bias = 0 and let the kernel pick a base via the normal mmap path.
After this patch it takes the probe-then-munmap path and sets
elf_flags |= MAP_FIXED_NOREPLACE.

The cover letter says "Fix this for the main binary" but the code
also affects the interpreter (ld.so) when it is the top-level binary
(e.g. "./ld.so ./myprog").  Is that intentional?  If so, it is worth
a sentence in the commit message.  If not, could the bump be placed
inside the if (interpreter) branch only?

Johannes Weiner <hannes@cmpxchg.org>

mm: switch THP shrinker to list_lru

The overall approach is sound and the NUMA-correctness fix is well
motivated.  A few observations below.

--- [PATCH v2 1/7] mm: list_lru: lock_list_lru_of_memcg() cannot return NULL if !skip_empty ---

The NULL removal is correct.  With skip_empty=false the MEMCG path
walks up the hierarchy until it finds a live ancestor or falls back to
the per-node lru; it never returns NULL.  The non-MEMCG stub
unconditionally returns &lru->node[nid].lru.  Both sides are safe.

--- [PATCH v2 5/7] mm: list_lru: introduce caller locking for additions and deletions ---

> +/**
> + * list_lru_lock: lock the sublist for the given node and memcg
> + * @lru: the lru pointer
> + * @nid: the node id of the sublist to lock.
> + * @memcg: the cgroup of the sublist to lock.
> + *
> + * Returns the locked list_lru_one sublist. The caller must call
> + * list_lru_unlock() when done.
> + *
> + * Return: the locked list_lru_one, or NULL on failure
> + */

The "or NULL on failure" in the kdoc contradicts the guarantee that
was just established in patch 1: with skip_empty=false the walk always
suceeds.  Could this be simplified to just "Return: the locked
list_lru_one"?

> +struct list_lru_one *list_lru_lock_irqsave(struct list_lru *lru, int nid,
> +		struct mem_cgroup *memcg, unsigned long *irq_flags);
> +void list_lru_unlock_irqrestore(struct list_lru_one *l,
> +		unsigned long *irq_flags);

The lock_list_lru()/unlock_list_lru() helpers now dispatch on
irq_flags != NULL first, then on the irq boolean.  When
list_lru_lock_irqsave() is called the flags pointer is non-NULL so
irqsave/irqrestore is used throughout, including on the retry path
when walking up the memcg hierarchy.  The save/restore pairing is
correct across retries.

--- [PATCH v2 7/7] mm: switch deferred split shrinker to list_lru ---

> +	if (list_lru_init_memcg(&deferred_split_lru, deferred_split_shrinker)) {
> +		shrinker_free(deferred_split_shrinker);
> +		return -ENOMEM;
> +	}
> +
>  	deferred_split_shrinker->count_objects = deferred_split_count;
>  	deferred_split_shrinker->scan_objects = deferred_split_scan;
>  	shrinker_register(deferred_split_shrinker);

This ordering looks correct: the list_lru is initialised before the
shrinker is registered, so the callbacks can safely access it from the
moment registration completes.

> +		if (!huge_zero_folio_shrinker) {
> +			list_lru_destroy(&deferred_split_lru);
>  			shrinker_free(deferred_split_shrinker);
>  			return -ENOMEM;
>  		}

The ordering here is inverted.  At this point deferred_split_shrinker
is already registered and its callbacks (deferred_split_count,
deferred_split_scan) access deferred_split_lru.  Calling
list_lru_destroy() while the shrinker is still live opens a window
where a concurrent do_shrink_slab() can walk a partially-destroyed
list_lru.  shrinker_free() calls wait_for_completion() to drain any
in-flight invocations before returning, so the safe order is:

        shrinker_free(deferred_split_shrinker);
        list_lru_destroy(&deferred_split_lru);

> +static void __init thp_shrinker_exit(void)
>  {
>  	shrinker_free(huge_zero_folio_shrinker);
> +	list_lru_destroy(&deferred_split_lru);
>  	shrinker_free(deferred_split_shrinker);
>  }

Same ordering issue: deferred_split_lru is torn down while
deferred_split_shrinker is still registered.  In practice this is
called only from the hugepage_init() error path during boot so the
window is narrow, but the correct sequence is still to free
deferred_split_shrinker before destroying the list it depends on:

        shrinker_free(deferred_split_shrinker);
        list_lru_destroy(&deferred_split_lru);
        shrinker_free(huge_zero_folio_shrinker);

Author: Michal Clapinski <mclapinski@google.com>

kho: fix deferred init of kho scratch

[ ... ]

> diff --git a/mm/mm_init.c b/mm/mm_init.c

[ ... ]

> @@ -2090,9 +2094,11 @@ deferred_init_memmap_chunk(unsigned long start_pfn, unsigned long end_pfn,
>  			unsigned long mo_pfn = ALIGN(spfn + 1, MAX_ORDER_NR_PAGES);
>  			unsigned long chunk_end = min(mo_pfn, epfn);
>  
> -			nr_pages += deferred_init_pages(zone, spfn, chunk_end);
> -			deferred_free_pages(spfn, chunk_end - spfn);
> +			// KHO scratch is MAX_ORDER_NR_PAGES aligned.
> +			if (!pfn_is_kho_scratch(spfn))
> +				deferred_init_pages(zone, spfn, chunk_end);
>  
> +			deferred_free_pages(spfn, chunk_end - spfn);
>  			spfn = chunk_end;
>  
>  			if (can_resched)
> @@ -2100,6 +2106,7 @@ deferred_init_memmap_chunk(unsigned long start_pfn, unsigned long end_pfn,
>  			else
>  				touch_nmi_watchdog();
>  		}
> +		nr_pages += epfn - spfn;
>  	}
>  
>  	return nr_pages;

The placement of `nr_pages += epfn - spfn` is wrong.  It is inside
the for_each_free_mem_range loop body but outside the inner
`while (spfn < epfn)` loop.  Because the while loop terminates only
when spfn reaches epfn, this expression always evaluates to zero.

deferred_grow_zone() is the only caller that inspects the return
value of deferred_init_memmap_chunk().  It uses it here:

  nr_pages += deferred_init_memmap_chunk(spfn, epfn, zone, false);
  ...
  pgdat->first_deferred_pfn = nr_pages ? spfn : ULONG_MAX;
  return nr_pages > 0;

With nr_pages perpetually 0, deferred_grow_zone() sets
first_deferred_pfn to ULONG_MAX on its very first invocation and
returns false, even though it just successfully initialized and freed
pages.  Any subsequent call short-circuits immediately.  This breaks
the on-demand zone-growing path that is exercised when an allocation
arrives before the background deferred-init kthreads have caught up.

The original code accumulated the count inside the inner loop:

  nr_pages += deferred_init_pages(zone, spfn, chunk_end);

Moving it out of the while loop and switching to `epfn - spfn` loses
that count entirely.  A straightforward fix is to restore the
accumulation inside the while loop:

  if (!pfn_is_kho_scratch(spfn))
    nr_pages += deferred_init_pages(zone, spfn, chunk_end);

If scratch pages should contribute to the count even though
deferred_init_pages is skipped for them, an alternative is to
save spfn before the loop and use `saved_spfn + (chunk_end - spfn)`
but the simpler form above preserves the original semantics (only
counting pages that were actually initialized).

Author: Lorenzo Stoakes (Oracle) <ljs@kernel.org>

mm: expand mmap_prepare functionality and usage

Overall the series has a clean direction. The vm_ops->mapped hook fills
a real gap, and the mmap_action_simple_ioremap() helper makes driver
conversions straightforward. Three issues below need to be addressed
before this lands.


--- [PATCH 04/15] mm: add vm_ops->mapped hook ---

> diff --git a/include/linux/fs.h b/include/linux/fs.h

[ ... ]

> +static inline int vfs_mmap(struct file *file, struct vm_area_struct *vma)
> +{
> +	int err;
> +
> +	if (file->f_op->mmap_prepare)
> +		return compat_vma_mmap(file, vma);
> +
> +	err = file->f_op->mmap(file, vma);
> +	if (err)
> +		return err;
> +
> +	return __vma_check_mmap_hook(vma);
> +}

> diff --git a/mm/util.c b/mm/util.c

[ ... ]

> +int __vma_check_mmap_hook(struct vm_area_struct *vma)
> +{
> +	/* vm_ops->mapped is not valid if mmap() is specified. */
> +	if (WARN_ON_ONCE(vma->vm_ops->mapped))
> +		return -EINVAL;
> +
> +	return 0;
> +}

vma->vm_ops is not guaranteed to be non-NULL here. Countless drivers
using the old f_op->mmap interface never set vma->vm_ops (remap_pfn_range
and io_remap_pfn_range do not set it either). If such a driver's mmap()
succeeds, __vma_check_mmap_hook() dereferences a NULL pointer. This is
a regression against the entire class of drivers that use f_op->mmap
without setting vm_ops.

The check should guard against a NULL vm_ops:

    if (vma->vm_ops && WARN_ON_ONCE(vma->vm_ops->mapped))


> +static int __compat_vma_mapped(struct file *file, struct vm_area_struct *vma)
> +{
> +	const struct vm_operations_struct *vm_ops = vma->vm_ops;
> +	void *vm_private_data = vma->vm_private_data;
> +	int err;
> +
> +	if (!vm_ops->mapped)
> +		return 0;

Same NULL pointer hazard here: if an mmap_prepare hook does not set
desc->vm_ops, then vma->vm_ops is NULL after compat_set_vma_from_desc(),
and vm_ops->mapped crashes before the intent of the check can execute.
Needs an early return on NULL vm_ops.

> +	err = vm_ops->mapped(vma->vm_start, vma->vm_end, vma->vm_pgoff, file,
> +			     &vm_private_data);
> +	if (err)
> +		unmap_vma_locked(vma);
> +	/* Update private data if changed. */
> +	if (vm_private_data != vma->vm_private_data)
> +		vma->vm_private_data = vm_private_data;

unmap_vma_locked() calls do_munmap(), which invokes vm_ops->close() and
then frees the VMA via vm_area_free(). The subsequent read of
vma->vm_private_data (in the comparison) and the conditional write
both occur on a freed object. Even for current callers where the
condition is false at runtime, the read itself is already a
use-after-free. The vm_private_data update must occur before any
error-path unmap, or be skipped entirely on the error path.


--- [PATCH 05/15] fs: afs: correctly drop reference count on mapping failure ---

> diff --git a/fs/afs/file.c b/fs/afs/file.c

[ ... ]

> +static int afs_file_mmap_prepare(struct vm_area_desc *desc)
> +{
> +	struct afs_vnode *vnode = AFS_FS_I(file_inode(desc->file));
> +	int ret;
> +
> +	afs_add_open_mmap(vnode);
> +
> +	ret = generic_file_mmap_prepare(desc);
> +	if (ret)
> +		return ret;
> +
> +	desc->vm_ops = &afs_vm_ops;
> +	return ret;
> +}
> +
> +static int afs_mapped(unsigned long start, unsigned long end, pgoff_t pgoff,
> +		      const struct file *file, void **vm_private_data)
> +{
> +	struct afs_vnode *vnode = AFS_FS_I(file_inode(file));
> +
> +	afs_add_open_mmap(vnode);
> +	return 0;
> +}

The commit message says the intent is to defer afs_add_open_mmap() from
mmap_prepare into the mapped callback. But the call in
afs_file_mmap_prepare() was not removed: both paths now call
afs_add_open_mmap(), leading to two bugs:

1. If generic_file_mmap_prepare() fails, afs_add_open_mmap() was called
   but the error return path no longer calls afs_drop_open_mmap(), so
   cb_nr_mmap leaks by one.

2. If the mapping succeeds and is not merged, afs_add_open_mmap() is
   called once in mmap_prepare and once in afs_mapped(), incrementing
   cb_nr_mmap by two. afs_vm_close() decrements by one, so a permanent
   reference leak occurs per new non-merged mapping.

The afs_add_open_mmap() call in afs_file_mmap_prepare() should be
removed entirely; afs_mapped() is the right and only place for it.


--- [PATCH 02/15] mm: add documentation for the mmap_prepare file operation callback ---

> diff --git a/Documentation/filesystems/mmap_prepare.rst b/Documentation/filesystems/mmap_prepare.rst

[ ... ]

> +.. code-block:: Cw

Typo in the RST directive: "Cw" should be "C".

> +where @desc is a pointer to `struct vma_area_desc`):
                                          ^^^^^^^^^^^

Should be "vm_area_desc", not "vma_area_desc".

