slab: support memoryless nodes with sheaves (3 patches)

The overall design is sound.  A few items worth discussing:

--- [PATCH 1/3] slab: decouple pointer to barn from kmem_cache_node ---

[ ... ]

> @@ -7545,15 +7545,20 @@ static void free_kmem_cache_nodes(struct kmem_cache *s)
> -	for_each_kmem_cache_node(s, node, n) {
> -		if (n->barn) {
> -			WARN_ON(n->barn->nr_full);
> -			WARN_ON(n->barn->nr_empty);
> -			kfree(n->barn);
> -			n->barn = NULL;
> -		}
> +	for_each_node(node) {
> +		struct node_barn *barn = get_barn_node(s, node);
> +
> +		if (!barn)
> +			continue;
> +
> +		WARN_ON(barn->nr_full);
> +		WARN_ON(barn->nr_empty);
> +		kfree(barn);
> +		s->per_node[node].barn = NULL;
> +	}
> +
> +	for_each_kmem_cache_node(s, node, n) {

The split into two loops is safe at destruction time, no concern there.

[ ... ]

> @@ -7579,31 +7579,36 @@ static int init_kmem_cache_nodes(struct kmem_cache *s)
> +	if (slab_state == DOWN || !cache_has_sheaves(s))
> +		return 1;
> +
> +	for_each_node_mask(node, slab_barn_nodes) {
> +		struct node_barn *barn;
> +
> +		barn = kmalloc_node(sizeof(*barn), GFP_KERNEL, node);
> +
> +		if (!barn)
> +			return 0;
> +
> +		barn_init(barn);
> +		s->per_node[node].barn = barn;
> +	}

If the second loop fails midway, some barns are attached to per_node[]
but slab_barn_nodes is already set for those nodes.  The partially
allocated barns will be cleaned up by free_kmem_cache_nodes() via the
caller's error path -- can you confirm that path is correct?  On
successful error recovery, the next init_kmem_cache_nodes() call for
a new cache will also iterate slab_barn_nodes and allocate barns for
nodes that already have one from a prior run, causing a double alloc.
Oh wait -- is that actually guarded somewhere?  In slub_cpu_setup() the
check is `get_barn_node(s, nid)`, but in the second loop here there is
no such guard.  If init_kmem_cache_nodes() is retried for the same
cache it should be harmless since init fails and the cache is destroyed,
but if a *different* new cache is created while slab_barn_nodes already
has the node set, wouldn't it enter this loop and double-allocate a
barn for a node that init_kmem_cache_nodes() hasn't seen partially fail
on?  I think on a fresh cache call the per_node[] barn pointers start
NULL so there is no double-alloc issue -- but an explicit check like
`if (!get_barn_node(s, node))` here would mirror the defensive guard
already present in slub_cpu_setup() and slab_mem_going_online_callback().

Note: the diff is truncated so bootstrap_cache_sheaves() changes from
patch 1 are not visible in this review.

--- [PATCH 2/3] slab: create barns for online memoryless nodes ---

[ ... ]

> +static int slub_cpu_setup(unsigned int cpu)
> +{
> +	int nid = cpu_to_node(cpu);
> +	struct kmem_cache *s;
> +	int ret = 0;
> +
> +	/*
> +	 * we never clear a nid so it's safe to do a quick check before taking
> +	 * the mutex, and then recheck to handle parallel cpu hotplug safely
> +	 */
> +	if (node_isset(nid, slab_barn_nodes))
> +		return 0;

The lockless read of slab_barn_nodes followed by the guarded recheck
under slab_mutex is correct given the monotonic-only write pattern.

> +	list_for_each_entry(s, &slab_caches, list) {
> +		struct node_barn *barn;
> +
> +		/*
> +		 * barn might already exist if a previous callback failed midway
> +		 */
> +		if (!cache_has_sheaves(s) || get_barn_node(s, nid))
> +			continue;
> +
> +		barn = kmalloc_node(sizeof(*barn), GFP_KERNEL, nid);
> +
> +		if (!barn) {
> +			ret = -ENOMEM;
> +			goto out;
> +		}
> +
> +		barn_init(barn);
> +		s->per_node[nid].barn = barn;
> +	}
> +	node_set(nid, slab_barn_nodes);

If slub_cpu_setup() fails partway through (ret = -ENOMEM, goto out
before node_set), some caches on nid have barns, others don't, and
slab_barn_nodes is NOT set for nid.  The next CPU on that nid will
retry; the `get_barn_node(s, nid)` guard correctly skips already-
allocated ones.  This recovery path looks fine.

However: what is the CPU hotplug error handling policy here?  If
slub_cpu_setup() returns -ENOMEM for CPUHP_SLUB_DEAD (a PREPARE-
section callback), does the hotplug framework abort bringing up the CPU
and guarantee that teardown callbacks are invoked to reclaim the
partial barns?  Or do they simply leak until the cache is destroyed?
The existing code for slab_mem_going_online_callback() has similar
partial-alloc semantics so this may already be an accepted pattern,
but it's worth a comment.

[ ... ]

> -		rcu_sheaf->node = numa_mem_id();
> +		rcu_sheaf->node = numa_node_id();

This is the key change that makes the RCU sheaf return to the barn of
the cpu's own (potentially memoryless) node rather than the nearest
memory node.  After patch 1 rcu_free_sheaf() looks up the barn via
get_barn_node(s, sheaf->node), and patch 2 ensures barns exist on
memoryless nodes, so the lookup will succeed.  Looks correct.

--- [PATCH 3/3] slab: free remote objects to sheaves on memoryless nodes ---

> +static __always_inline bool can_free_to_pcs(struct slab *slab)
> +{
> +	int slab_node;
> +	int numa_node;
> +
> +	if (!IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_NUMA))
> +		goto check_pfmemalloc;
> +
> +	slab_node = slab_nid(slab);
